/ Kessel [red label]; “California Academy/ of Sciences/ 
<typeStatus box="[1267,1323,1161,1185]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Type</typeStatus>
No. 
<number box="[1380,1436,1159,1184]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="6452.0">6452</number>
[dissected, first flagellomere and arista missing from antenna] (
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34700" box="[860,920,1196,1220]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15690" name="California Academy of Sciences" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">CAS</collectionCode>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,1725]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,821,1231,1256]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Geographical distribution and seasonal occurrence</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[840,927,1231,1256]" captionStart="FIGURE 71" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1988,2010]" captionTargetBox="[166,1410,506,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[165,1417,501,1963]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 71. Known distribution of C. arnaudi, C. bertae, and C. browni." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/271494/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
Fig. 
<number box="[896,927,1232,1256]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="71.0">71</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[951,1149,1231,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertae">
<emphasis box="[951,1149,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Callomyia bertae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[151,249,1268,1293]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">holotype</typeStatus>
collected from the Pinos Altos Mountains in Grant County, New 
<collectingCountry box="[984,1073,1268,1293]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, in late August.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="516" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,1725]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1303,1328]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[321,516,1303,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertae">
<emphasis box="[321,516,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Callomyia bertae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to the Nearctic species 
<taxonomicName box="[974,1100,1304,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="proxima">
<emphasis box="[974,993,1304,1327]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1007,1100,1305,1328]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">proxima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Palaearctic species 
<taxonomicName authority="Shatalkin" authorityName="Shatalkin" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dorsimaculata">
<emphasis box="[1410,1429,1304,1327]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,313,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">dorsimaculata</emphasis>
Shatalkin
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[439,557,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis box="[439,458,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[472,557,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[619,730,1341,1364]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sonora">
<emphasis box="[619,638,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[652,730,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">sonora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as shown in the strict consensus tree (
<figureCitation box="[1165,1249,1340,1365]" captionStart="FIGURE 79" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[152,1430,205,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[151,1436,195,1845]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 79. Strict consensus tree of the 136 most parsimonious cladograms of the world species of Callomyia and outgroups, produced by the analysis of the data matrix in Table 2. Bremer support values are listed above each internode. The Oriental species, Callomyia coei Kessel and C. triangulata Tkoč, were excluded from the analysis because they are only known from females." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/271502/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
Fig. 
<number box="[1217,1249,1340,1364]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="79.0">79</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,1725]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
A series of seven female specimens from Durango, 
<collectingCountry box="[788,873,1375,1400]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[890,973,1375,1400]" captionStart="FIGURE 71" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1988,2010]" captionTargetBox="[166,1410,506,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[165,1417,501,1963]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 71. Known distribution of C. arnaudi, C. bertae, and C. browni." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/271494/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
Fig. 
<number box="[944,973,1376,1400]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="71.0">71</number>
</figureCitation>
) may be conspecific with the male of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertae">
<emphasis box="[1410,1429,1376,1399]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,223,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">bertae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on similarities in colour. Five specimens are from 
<quantity box="[920,1021,1412,1437]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.609344" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" unit="mi" value="10.0">10 miles</quantity>
west of El Salto, collected on 
<date pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="1964-06-14" valueMax="1964-06-21" valueMin="1964-06-14">
<number pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="17.5" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="14.0">14- 21</number>
.vi. 
<number box="[210,271,1447,1472]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="1964.0">1964</number>
</date>
at 
<quantity box="[303,408,1447,1472]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7432" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" unit="ft" value="9000.0">9000 feet</quantity>
and two specimens are from 
<quantity box="[734,829,1447,1472]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2530816" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" unit="mi" value="14.0">14 miles</quantity>
southwest of El Salto, collected on 
<date box="[1228,1348,1447,1472]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="1964-06-26">
<number box="[1228,1258,1447,1472]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="26.0">26</number>
.vi. 
<number box="[1288,1348,1447,1472]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="1964.0">1964</number>
</date>
at 
<quantity metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4384" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" unit="ft" value="8000.0">8000 feet</quantity>
(all collected by J.F. McAlpine, deposited in 
<collectionCode box="[710,772,1484,1508]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/y2kv-9w3k" name="Canadian National Collection of Insects, Arachnids, and Nematodes" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">CNC</collectionCode>
). These females (
<figureCitation box="[969,1056,1484,1509]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 − 28" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1906,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,373,1885]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 25 − 28. Callomyia females, lateral view. 25. C. arnaudi (pale orange on tergites 1 – 2 mostly obscured in photograph by silver-white dusting). 26. Possible C. bertae female. 27. C. calla. 28. C. corvina." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/271483/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Figs 26</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1069,1098,1484,1508]" captionStart="FIGURES 33 − 36" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1537,1559]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1512]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,193,1516]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 33 − 36. Callomyia females, dorsal view. 33. C. arnaudi (pale orange on tergites 1 – 2 mostly obscured in photograph by silver-white dusting). 34. Possible C. bertae female. 35. C. calla. 36. C. corvina." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/271485/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">34</figureCitation>
) have similar metallic bluishwhite thoracic and abdominal colour patterns to the females of 
<taxonomicName box="[892,1017,1519,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arnaudi">
<emphasis box="[892,911,1520,1543]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[928,1017,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">arnaudi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(which is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[1265,1372,1519,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertae">
<emphasis box="[1265,1284,1520,1543]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1300,1372,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">bertae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
—see “Diagnosis above), but abdominal tergite 
<number box="[635,649,1556,1580]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="4.0">4</number>
is entirely metallic bluish-white and is not interrupted by a median dorsal dark band. In addition, these females are larger in size than those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1022,1146,1591,1616]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arnaudi">
<emphasis box="[1022,1041,1592,1615]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1057,1146,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">arnaudi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They are also similar in appearance to the females of 
<taxonomicName box="[479,657,1628,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilloglyorum">
<emphasis box="[479,498,1629,1652]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[512,657,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">gilloglyorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of similar thoracic and abdominal colour patterns. However, the colour of the potential 
<taxonomicName box="[451,555,1663,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertae">
<emphasis box="[451,470,1664,1687]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[484,555,1663,1688]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">bertae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females is more metallic bluish-white than silver-grey and abdominal tergites 2, 4 and 
<number box="[247,261,1700,1725]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="6.0">6</number>
are complete and not interrupted by a median dorsal dark band.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
